3. How to call Power Apps to Power Automate:-

In my experience, we can call Power Automate from Power Apps by creating an instant cloud flow with the Power Apps trigger. 
First, I create a flow in Power Automate and select the 'Power Apps' trigger. 
Then I define the required input parameters such as ID, name, or any field that I want to pass from Power Apps. 
After creating the flow logic, like sending an email or updating Dataverse, I save the flow.

Then in Power Apps, I connect the flow using the Power Automate option and call it using the FlowName.Run() function. 
For example, when a user clicks a Submit button, I call the flow and pass the required parameters. 
This way, Power Apps triggers Power Automate to perform background operations like approvals, notifications.
â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”â”

4. Explain real-time challenges you faced while developing an app and how you overcame them?

I have faced a some of few challenges:
While developing the export-to-Excel functionality in my application, 
Business users wanted to export filtered records from a Gallery directly into Excel, but Power Apps does not have a built-in feature to generate Excel files. 

â€” In my project,
when users wanted to export Gallery data to Excel, I handled it using Power Apps and Power Automate together. 
When the user clicks the Export button, I pass the Gallery data to Power Automate in JSON format using the JSON function.
I use ShowColumns to send only the required fields instead of all columns, which improves performance. (ShowColumns(EmployeeList, "EmployeeName", "EmployeeID"))

Now in Power Automate, the data is received as a JSON string, so the first thing I do is use the Parse JSON action.
This step is very important because it converts the JSON text into structured data so that I can access individual fields.
After that, I can easily use those fields in actions like Create CSV table, 
then I use the Create file action in SharePoint or OneDrive for Busines to store the file.
Finally, I generate a shareable link and send it back in power apps so that user can download the Excel file. 

  ("I use JSON format because it is the standard way to send structured data from Power Apps to Power Automate. 
  When I export data from a Gallery, there are multiple records and multiple fields, 
  so JSON helps represent that data in a structured format with key-value pairs.")

â€” One more i faced the challenge is Deligation, 
I faced while working with large datasets in Power Apps was dealing with delegation limits when connecting to a SharePoint list with thousands of records. 
By default, Power Apps was only loading 500 records, which meant users couldnâ€™t access the complete data they needed.
To resolve this, I first optimized my formulas by using delegable functions,
which allowed Power Apps to query data directly from SharePoint instead of loading it locally. 
his significantly improved data retrieval and ensured users could access relevant records efficiently.

However, in some scenarios where delegation was still not fully supported, 
I implemented Pagination to manage large datasets more effectively.
Instead of loading all records at once, I displayed a fixed number of records per page, such as 50, 100, 200, 500.

I achieved this by:
Creating variables to track the current page number and page size
Using functions like FirstN() and LastN() to display only the required records for each page
Adding Next and Previous buttons so users could navigate easily between pages.
This approach improves app performance, reduces data load, and provides a better user experience, especially when working with large datasets.
