6. How do you manage permissions in PowerApps?

In my project, 
I implemented role-based permissions using Azure AD groups. 
I connected the Office365Groups connector in Power Apps and used the App OnStart property to check whether the logged-in user belongs to a specific group.
I created a global variable using the Set() function and used Office365Groups.IsMemberOfGroup function to verify the userâ€™s group membership. 
This variable stores true or false based on whether the user is a member of that Azure AD group. 
For example:- 
In the App OnStart property, I used the User().Email function and stored the userâ€™s role in a global variable:
âœ… Set(varIsManager, Office365Groups.IsMemberOfGroup("GroupID", User().Email).value)
Based on this variable, 
I use control permissions, such as showing or hiding buttons, enabling edit access, or restricting certain features. 
This approach helps implement role-based access control dynamically when the app starts.

In SharePoint:
I manage permissions using SharePoint list permissions. I assign users or groups with permission levels like Read, Contribute, or Edit.
First, I create groups like Admins, Manager, and Users based on business requirements. 
Then I assign permission levels like Read for view-only access, Contribute for adding and editing records, and Full Control for complete access. 
For example:- 
In the App OnStart property, I used the User().Email function and stored the userâ€™s role in a global variable:
âœ… Set(userRole, LookUp(SecurityRoleList, UserEmail = User().Email, Role))
Based on this variable, 
I use control permissions, such as showing or hiding buttons, enabling edit access, or restricting certain features.
This ensures users only have the permissions required for their role.

In Dataverse:
I manage permissions using security roles, which control what users can access and what actions they can perform on specific tables. 
First, I create a security role in the Power Platform Admin Center and define permissions like Create, Read, Write, Delete for the required tables.
Then I assign those roles to users. This ensures users can only access the data based on their role.
